1
00:00:08,467 --> 00:00:13,054
Wait. We shouldn't...
We shouldn't be doing this.

2
00:00:13,430 --> 00:00:16,015
What? You're not having fun?

3
00:00:16,558 --> 00:00:18,226
It's not that. I just...

4
00:00:18,352 --> 00:00:20,019
Rather be with the boys?

5
00:00:20,771 --> 00:00:22,397
No.

6
00:00:22,523 --> 00:00:24,273
Well, then come on.

7
00:00:37,329 --> 00:00:38,538
You kids need any help?

8
00:00:38,664 --> 00:00:39,956
No. No, we're fine.

9
00:00:40,082 --> 00:00:41,582
Car trouble?

10
00:00:41,709 --> 00:00:42,542
No.

11
00:00:42,668 --> 00:00:43,918
Then why are you here?

12
00:00:44,044 --> 00:00:45,878
We're just talking.

13
00:00:46,964 --> 00:00:48,965
Does she do all the talking?

14
00:00:49,091 --> 00:00:50,717
Most of it.

15
00:00:53,220 --> 00:00:54,929
I know what that's like.

16
00:00:55,889 --> 00:00:58,182
I'm gonna come back
through here in 10 minutes,

17
00:00:58,308 --> 00:01:01,978
and if you're still here,
I'm gonna call your parents.

18
00:01:02,980 --> 00:01:05,440
Yes, sir. Thank you.

19
00:01:13,866 --> 00:01:16,200
Now, where were we?

20
00:01:16,326 --> 00:01:18,161
We were going.

21
00:01:18,287 --> 00:01:19,829
In nine minutes.

22
00:01:37,264 --> 00:01:38,556
Wait...

23
00:01:38,682 --> 00:01:40,141
Stevie? What's wrong?

24
00:01:46,231 --> 00:01:47,523
Oh, my God!

25
00:01:50,444 --> 00:01:53,196
Help! Someone help me!

26
00:03:32,004 --> 00:03:34,630
Sixteen-year-old
with respiratory arrest.

27
00:03:35,257 --> 00:03:37,717
The only thing I hate more
than a thief is a crippled thief.

28
00:03:37,843 --> 00:03:39,719
Yeah, me, too.
No sign of trauma, no history

29
00:03:39,845 --> 00:03:41,512
- of asthma or...
- Who the hell is J. Whitner?

30
00:03:41,680 --> 00:03:45,850
No idea. Stevie Lipa's EKG
and echocardiogram were normal, but...

31
00:03:45,976 --> 00:03:48,144
Normal is good. Send him home.

32
00:03:48,270 --> 00:03:52,523
J. Whitner, doctor. Who is he,
and where do I find him?

33
00:03:52,649 --> 00:03:54,609
She's the new researcher,
works with Ereshevsky.

34
00:03:54,735 --> 00:03:56,402
- Is she hot?
- She's in a wheelchair.

35
00:03:56,528 --> 00:03:57,612
Doesn't mean she's not hot.

36
00:03:57,738 --> 00:03:59,238
Just means she can't bend over,

37
00:03:59,364 --> 00:04:01,324
so Cuddy has to
bend over backwards.

38
00:04:01,450 --> 00:04:06,162
Sixteen-year-old kid. ER workup revealed
a bloody pleural effusion.

39
00:04:06,288 --> 00:04:08,915
- That's odd.
- Yeah, that occurred to me.

40
00:04:09,041 --> 00:04:10,666
What took you so long
to mention it?

41
00:04:10,792 --> 00:04:12,668
No tumors or pneumonia
on the CT.

42
00:04:12,794 --> 00:04:15,004
He passed out while making out.

43
00:04:15,130 --> 00:04:17,924
If he's into sex, drugs and rock
and roll can't be that far behind.

44
00:04:18,050 --> 00:04:19,216
I'm guessing cocaine.

45
00:04:19,343 --> 00:04:20,468
Tox screen was clean.

46
00:04:20,594 --> 00:04:23,054
Just means he wasn't on drugs,
not that he hasn't been using drugs.

47
00:04:23,180 --> 00:04:25,973
Looks like a plumbing problem
to me. Leaky pipes.

48
00:04:26,099 --> 00:04:28,459
If he popped an aneurysm,
he'd be in the morgue, not the ER.

49
00:04:28,518 --> 00:04:30,895
That's why you're gonna do a venogram
instead of an arteriogram.

50
00:04:31,021 --> 00:04:33,397
This is not a high-pressure burst.
It's a low-pressure leak.

51
00:04:33,523 --> 00:04:36,233
Still could've been drugs that caused
the pipes to corrode in the first place.

52
00:04:36,360 --> 00:04:37,693
So go look under his mattress.

53
00:04:37,819 --> 00:04:40,821
See if he's got any pills or powder
stashed with the hand lotion.

54
00:04:56,129 --> 00:05:00,633
Sweet ride. I asked for the one
with the sissy bar and the banana seat,

55
00:05:00,759 --> 00:05:05,012
but Santa gave me this instead. Guess
that's what I get for being naughty.

56
00:05:05,973 --> 00:05:07,682
You must be Dr. House.

57
00:05:07,808 --> 00:05:08,641
Yeah.

58
00:05:09,267 --> 00:05:12,311
So looks like there's been some sort
of mix-up at the parking office.

59
00:05:12,437 --> 00:05:14,146
They had to move me closer
to the door.

60
00:05:14,272 --> 00:05:17,858
Had to? You don't look like
the type to pull a weapon.

61
00:05:17,985 --> 00:05:19,694
- Wheelchair.
- Cane.

62
00:05:20,153 --> 00:05:23,322
I think you should do the honorable
thing and let me have my space back.

63
00:05:23,448 --> 00:05:26,617
Oh, well,
since you asked so nicely, wheelchair.

64
00:05:27,285 --> 00:05:30,997
Cane. Walking long distances
makes my leg hurt.

65
00:05:31,123 --> 00:05:32,623
And it's easy for me?

66
00:05:32,749 --> 00:05:35,042
Of course not.
Pushing that little lever?

67
00:05:35,168 --> 00:05:39,296
The muscles must burn. I'm sure
the last 10 yards are pure torture.

68
00:05:39,423 --> 00:05:41,664
Crossing the parking lot is dangerous.
Cars can't see me.

69
00:05:41,717 --> 00:05:44,010
You ever hit a patch
of black ice with a cane?

70
00:05:44,136 --> 00:05:47,722
No, gosh, on account of the fact
that I can't walk.

71
00:05:47,848 --> 00:05:50,683
Maybe you should ask the parking office
for some crampons.

72
00:05:50,809 --> 00:05:55,688
This is about who can most easily cross
the parking lot. You're the winner.

73
00:05:55,814 --> 00:05:58,899
Oh, and the prize
is apparently a parking space.

74
00:06:08,618 --> 00:06:11,299
There's still no answer at either
one of your parent's cell numbers.

75
00:06:11,413 --> 00:06:13,622
Is there any other way
we might be able to contact them?

76
00:06:13,749 --> 00:06:17,209
No, they're in a conference.

77
00:06:17,544 --> 00:06:19,462
They probably had
to turn them off or something.

78
00:06:19,588 --> 00:06:21,829
What does it matter where they are?
I mean, he's in pain.

79
00:06:21,923 --> 00:06:22,965
You gotta do something.

80
00:06:23,091 --> 00:06:24,216
We need them to sign this.

81
00:06:24,342 --> 00:06:26,427
Why can't he just
sign the papers? He's 16.

82
00:06:26,553 --> 00:06:27,928
Still not an adult.

83
00:06:28,055 --> 00:06:30,848
Then call my parents. They know him,
and they'll take responsibility,

84
00:06:30,974 --> 00:06:32,475
- do whatever you need.
- I can't. It won't...

85
00:06:32,601 --> 00:06:35,269
You can't just let him sit here in agony
until his parents finally decide...

86
00:06:35,395 --> 00:06:37,354
Leah, it's okay.

87
00:06:37,481 --> 00:06:39,440
No, it's not.

88
00:06:41,485 --> 00:06:44,862
I feel like there's an anvil
sitting on my chest.

89
00:07:02,089 --> 00:07:07,134
You win. I'm doing the venogram now.
We'll deal with the fallout later.

90
00:07:18,271 --> 00:07:20,106
My fingers feel wet.

91
00:07:20,232 --> 00:07:22,566
That's just the dye.
Your nerves can't tell the difference

92
00:07:22,692 --> 00:07:25,212
between the cold inside your body
and the wet outside your body.

93
00:07:25,237 --> 00:07:27,321
The nerves can't tell the difference,

94
00:07:27,447 --> 00:07:29,782
or the brain can't interpret
the difference?

95
00:07:29,908 --> 00:07:32,952
A little of both.
You like science?

96
00:07:37,833 --> 00:07:40,042
Looks like a diffusion pattern.

97
00:07:40,168 --> 00:07:42,711
That's because it's
the venous side. Low pressure.

98
00:07:42,838 --> 00:07:44,839
So Graham's law applies.

99
00:07:45,799 --> 00:07:47,633
You've taken physics already?

100
00:07:47,759 --> 00:07:50,427
No, I just sort of
read up on my own.

101
00:07:50,554 --> 00:07:54,098
I had to teach myself a lot of stuff,
too. Schools sucked where I grew up.

102
00:07:54,224 --> 00:07:56,142
You go to public or private?

103
00:07:56,268 --> 00:07:57,184
Public.

104
00:07:58,520 --> 00:08:02,189
Leak has to be in the pulmonary veins
to get in my lungs, right?

105
00:08:02,315 --> 00:08:03,357
Yep.

106
00:08:03,483 --> 00:08:05,192
I don't see anything. Do you?

107
00:08:05,318 --> 00:08:06,777
No.

108
00:08:06,903 --> 00:08:08,612
It doesn't make sense.

109
00:08:08,738 --> 00:08:12,616
How can I have a bloody effusion
without any bleeding?

110
00:08:30,552 --> 00:08:32,469
This is putrid.

111
00:08:32,596 --> 00:08:36,473
Put food-borne parasites and infections
on the list to check on.

112
00:08:38,435 --> 00:08:40,060
I'll take the bedroom.

113
00:08:51,948 --> 00:08:54,575
Oh. Sorry, I didn't know
there was anyone.

114
00:08:54,701 --> 00:08:57,786
- We were just...
- Oh, God! I have a gun.

115
00:08:58,872 --> 00:09:01,272
Look, you can take whatever you want.
My wallet's in my suit.

116
00:09:01,333 --> 00:09:02,791
Freeze! Freeze!

117
00:09:02,918 --> 00:09:04,126
I'm calling the cops.

118
00:09:04,252 --> 00:09:08,380
Okay, you don't have a gun,
and you're not calling the cops.

119
00:09:08,506 --> 00:09:11,267
Oh, no, I'm calling the cops unless
you two get out of here right now.

120
00:09:11,343 --> 00:09:15,596
"Unless"? Who calls the cops
unless a burglar does something?

121
00:09:19,851 --> 00:09:21,611
You don't want to
have to explain the affair.

122
00:09:21,728 --> 00:09:22,978
We're not having an affair.

123
00:09:24,773 --> 00:09:26,482
He's got a ring. You don't.

124
00:09:26,608 --> 00:09:28,776
And judging from the state
of the kitchen downstairs

125
00:09:28,902 --> 00:09:31,320
and the half-vacuumed bedroom,

126
00:09:31,446 --> 00:09:34,156
I'm guessing you're a better lover
than you are a maid.

127
00:09:34,282 --> 00:09:38,118
Maid? You son of a bitch.

128
00:09:38,245 --> 00:09:42,248
I'm not a maid, okay?
This is my house, not his.

129
00:09:43,750 --> 00:09:45,709
- Sorry.
- And what's wrong with my kitchen?

130
00:09:45,835 --> 00:09:49,255
Nothing. We're sorry.
We're just here to help Stevie.

131
00:09:50,590 --> 00:09:51,757
Who's Stevie?

132
00:09:51,883 --> 00:09:53,509
Your son?

133
00:09:57,555 --> 00:09:59,306
It was the address you gave.

134
00:09:59,432 --> 00:10:00,952
The ER must have
written it down wrong.

135
00:10:00,976 --> 00:10:03,227
Or you lied because you don't want us
to talk to your parents.

136
00:10:03,353 --> 00:10:04,687
I gave you their phone numbers.

137
00:10:04,813 --> 00:10:07,481
You gave us some numbers.
We haven't been able to reach anyone.

138
00:10:07,607 --> 00:10:09,208
I told you,
they must be in a conference.

139
00:10:09,317 --> 00:10:10,776
- He's lying.
- Leah.

140
00:10:11,778 --> 00:10:14,989
He's Romany, a Gypsy.

141
00:10:17,117 --> 00:10:18,617
So you don't have a home?

142
00:10:18,743 --> 00:10:20,244
Of course we do.

143
00:10:20,370 --> 00:10:23,247
What, next you're gonna ask me
about dancing around campfires

144
00:10:23,373 --> 00:10:26,875
and stealing children?
This is why I don't tell people.

145
00:10:27,002 --> 00:10:28,482
They share everything with each other

146
00:10:28,586 --> 00:10:31,505
and nothing with the gadje,
the outsiders.

147
00:10:31,631 --> 00:10:35,884
Sharing information with outsiders
has not gone so well for my people.

148
00:10:36,928 --> 00:10:40,055
Right now you're making yourself
more vulnerable by lying to us.

149
00:10:40,181 --> 00:10:43,434
You can't go to my house.
You'll pollute it.

150
00:10:43,560 --> 00:10:44,881
All we're gonna do
is look around.

151
00:10:44,894 --> 00:10:46,353
Your presence is enough.

152
00:10:48,440 --> 00:10:51,567
My parents take it seriously.

153
00:10:51,693 --> 00:10:53,819
It's spiritual
as much as it is physical.

154
00:10:53,945 --> 00:10:54,987
You know where he lives?

155
00:10:55,113 --> 00:10:56,447
Don't.

156
00:10:56,573 --> 00:10:58,407
Look, I'll tell you
whatever you need to know.

157
00:10:58,533 --> 00:10:59,813
If we can't
trust your answers...

158
00:10:59,826 --> 00:11:02,995
I drink sometimes, okay?
I've smoked pot.

159
00:11:03,121 --> 00:11:06,749
I'll tell you anything,
the truth. You just...

160
00:11:08,585 --> 00:11:10,336
You can't go in my home.

161
00:11:12,255 --> 00:11:16,091
The pot wouldn't cause a bleeding
problem. A pesticide on the pot could.

162
00:11:16,217 --> 00:11:18,093
Where did you get it?

163
00:11:18,219 --> 00:11:19,303
Some kid at school.

164
00:11:19,429 --> 00:11:21,597
Stevie. He got the pot from me.

165
00:11:21,723 --> 00:11:23,682
He doesn't even go to school.
His parents made him drop out.

166
00:11:23,808 --> 00:11:25,893
- I'm home-schooled.
- He reads books.

167
00:11:26,019 --> 00:11:29,646
What else are you lying about?
Is your father really a professor?

168
00:11:30,106 --> 00:11:31,357
He's a salesman.

169
00:11:31,483 --> 00:11:33,859
They buy and sell anything
they can get their hands on.

170
00:11:33,985 --> 00:11:36,445
They? So you're with your dad
when he's making these deals?

171
00:11:36,571 --> 00:11:38,781
He was just in Chicago
a week ago.

172
00:11:38,907 --> 00:11:42,993
- You fly?
- No, my dad's got a truck.

173
00:11:49,751 --> 00:11:51,210
You can't be serious.

174
00:11:51,336 --> 00:11:52,336
Actually, I can.

175
00:11:54,005 --> 00:11:56,382
See? It's my space.
I want it back.

176
00:11:56,508 --> 00:11:59,009
It's not your space.
It's the hospital's space,

177
00:11:59,135 --> 00:12:02,221
and the hospital thinks
that the person who's worse off

178
00:12:02,347 --> 00:12:04,056
should get the better space.

179
00:12:04,182 --> 00:12:07,267
Your application for a handicap space
says you can walk 50 yards.

180
00:12:07,394 --> 00:12:09,686
And Whitner's says
she can roll 50 miles

181
00:12:09,813 --> 00:12:12,022
between oil changes.
I can't change my leg.

182
00:12:12,148 --> 00:12:15,609
The space I moved you to is only
46 yards away from the front door.

183
00:12:15,735 --> 00:12:17,236
- I measured. You'll be fine.
- Great.

184
00:12:17,362 --> 00:12:21,407
So I can collapse four yards into the
lobby instead of outside in the cold.

185
00:12:21,533 --> 00:12:23,200
- As long as it's not in my office.
- Do you know who won

186
00:12:23,326 --> 00:12:27,329
the New York City Marathon
six years in a row? Guy in a wheelchair.

187
00:12:27,455 --> 00:12:29,331
Then go get yourself one,
and leave me alone.

188
00:12:29,457 --> 00:12:31,792
Give me my space,
I'll be happy to roll around all day.

189
00:12:33,002 --> 00:12:35,087
You couldn't last one week
in a wheelchair.

190
00:12:35,839 --> 00:12:36,672
Wanna bet?

191
00:12:41,553 --> 00:12:42,553
What's wrong with you?

192
00:12:42,679 --> 00:12:45,139
Nothing that a week off
my feet won't solve.

193
00:12:45,265 --> 00:12:46,765
Venogram's negative. No leak.

194
00:12:46,891 --> 00:12:48,016
You mean you couldn't
find the leak.

195
00:12:48,143 --> 00:12:48,976
Is your leg worse?

196
00:12:49,102 --> 00:12:51,478
No, my parking spot is.

197
00:12:51,604 --> 00:12:54,022
Blood is only made inside
the circulatory system,

198
00:12:54,149 --> 00:12:56,108
- which means when we find it outside...
- There's no leak.

199
00:12:56,234 --> 00:12:57,776
- I even checked lymphatics.
- So you're gonna spend a week

200
00:12:57,902 --> 00:13:00,320
in a wheelchair just to get a
parking space closer to the front door?

201
00:13:00,447 --> 00:13:02,030
Easier than chopping off my legs.

202
00:13:02,157 --> 00:13:03,437
We've ruled out toxins
and drugs.

203
00:13:03,533 --> 00:13:07,286
Kind of. He's Romany. Apparently,
they feel the need to keep secrets,

204
00:13:07,412 --> 00:13:08,996
so it's hard to know
anything for sure.

205
00:13:09,122 --> 00:13:10,581
Yeah, he's also a human being,

206
00:13:10,707 --> 00:13:12,458
which means you shouldn't be
trusting him to begin with.

207
00:13:12,584 --> 00:13:14,877
Stop relying on his answers
and find some on your own.

208
00:13:15,003 --> 00:13:16,462
It's a deep-vein thrombosis.

209
00:13:16,588 --> 00:13:19,298
The kid spent 16 hours
in the back seat of an old pick-up.

210
00:13:19,424 --> 00:13:21,258
Causes a clot,
makes its way to his lungs.

211
00:13:21,384 --> 00:13:23,784
We should do an arteriogram,
find the clot, bust it with TPA.

212
00:13:23,887 --> 00:13:24,847
Or we can find the leak.

213
00:13:24,971 --> 00:13:26,221
There's no leak.

214
00:13:26,347 --> 00:13:29,808
Hey, you can't yell at a guy
in a wheelchair.

215
00:13:31,186 --> 00:13:33,687
This is a slow leak.
You've got to speed it up.

216
00:13:33,813 --> 00:13:35,314
Thin his blood.
Redo the venogram.

217
00:13:35,440 --> 00:13:37,107
That could cause
a massive bleed.

218
00:13:37,233 --> 00:13:39,693
Excellent.
Massive will be even easier to find.

219
00:13:39,819 --> 00:13:43,155
Pardon me. I guess you guys
are gonna have to get the next one.

220
00:13:47,285 --> 00:13:49,369
I thought you were
redoing the venogram.

221
00:13:49,496 --> 00:13:51,330
As soon as we're done
with the arteriogram.

222
00:13:52,665 --> 00:13:55,209
Okay, you're gonna feel
a little poke.

223
00:13:57,504 --> 00:13:59,630
Can you maybe do that?

224
00:13:59,756 --> 00:14:02,257
Don't worry. It's just your leg. I don't
have to go any further than this.

225
00:14:02,383 --> 00:14:05,427
Take a look at this,
bones of your forearm.

226
00:14:06,137 --> 00:14:07,262
Radius and ulna.

227
00:14:07,388 --> 00:14:08,472
How about the wrist?

228
00:14:09,516 --> 00:14:13,685
Lunate, hamate, the...

229
00:14:14,270 --> 00:14:17,481
"Scared lovers try positions
they can't handle."

230
00:14:20,485 --> 00:14:24,196
It's a mnemonic for the wrist bones.
It's the only way I can remember them.

231
00:14:33,623 --> 00:14:34,998
You okay?

232
00:14:36,459 --> 00:14:38,293
- My stomach.
- Did you hit something?

233
00:14:38,419 --> 00:14:40,212
- I barely started.
- Lie flat.

234
00:14:40,338 --> 00:14:42,378
- No, I can't. It hurts too much.
- I'm getting out.

235
00:14:42,465 --> 00:14:43,882
It's our only chance
to see what's going on.

236
00:14:44,008 --> 00:14:45,759
If he moves,
I could shred his artery.

237
00:14:45,885 --> 00:14:46,718
Get it out now!

238
00:14:46,844 --> 00:14:49,846
It's gonna be okay, Stevie.
Just inject the dye.

239
00:14:52,850 --> 00:14:54,685
Dye's going into his liver,
but it's not coming out.

240
00:14:54,811 --> 00:14:57,092
Clot's gotta be constricting
the flow in the hepatic vein.

241
