312
00:18:34,113 --> 00:18:36,072
It says, "No admittance."

313
00:18:36,574 --> 00:18:38,325
- What's wrong with our son?
- We don't know yet.

314
00:18:38,451 --> 00:18:40,911
He's not gonna die, is he?

315
00:18:42,580 --> 00:18:45,457
Your son is very ill.
We're still trying to figure out why,

316
00:18:45,583 --> 00:18:48,251
which is why
we need you to leave the room.

317
00:19:06,229 --> 00:19:08,522
What are you gonna do now?

318
00:19:08,648 --> 00:19:12,567
Oh, now I've got to slide my butt
from one padded seat to another.

319
00:19:12,693 --> 00:19:14,778
What if I bump my knee?

320
00:19:15,947 --> 00:19:17,948
MRI showed
a granuloma in his liver.

321
00:19:18,074 --> 00:19:19,658
Fantastic.

322
00:19:20,868 --> 00:19:22,661
- Wanna give me a hand here?
- No.

323
00:19:22,787 --> 00:19:25,080
Clotting, bleeding and a granuloma
equals Wegener's.

324
00:19:25,206 --> 00:19:28,124
I know. That's why I said fantastic.
I was being sincere.

325
00:19:28,251 --> 00:19:30,085
- Now, give me a hand.
- Wouldn't be fair.

326
00:19:30,211 --> 00:19:31,878
We're gonna biopsy
the liver to confirm.

327
00:19:32,004 --> 00:19:33,255
Wouldn't be fair not to.

328
00:19:33,381 --> 00:19:37,050
People are good and kind and gentle
and help people in wheelchairs.

329
00:19:37,176 --> 00:19:38,802
- You don't believe that.
- But you do.

330
00:19:38,928 --> 00:19:40,637
No, I don't.

331
00:19:41,556 --> 00:19:43,807
Foreman, forget the biopsy.

332
00:19:43,933 --> 00:19:45,684
His liver will be gone
before you get the results.

333
00:19:45,810 --> 00:19:47,269
Start treatment
with cyclophosphamide

334
00:19:47,395 --> 00:19:50,897
before the Wegener's
punches a hole in another pipe.

335
00:20:16,757 --> 00:20:20,093
What's with the clothes?
You're not being discharged.

336
00:20:20,219 --> 00:20:21,928
I know.

337
00:20:23,222 --> 00:20:26,224
It's my parents.
They insist that I wear this stuff.

338
00:20:26,350 --> 00:20:30,103
We insist on our own food,
gown and furnishings for a reason.

339
00:20:30,229 --> 00:20:34,107
Hey, my chest burns.
Are you sure the treatments are working?

340
00:20:34,233 --> 00:20:36,443
Wegener's causes the body
to attack itself.

341
00:20:36,569 --> 00:20:38,862
That doesn't get undone
overnight. Be patient.

342
00:20:38,988 --> 00:20:41,364
- Where's your soup?
- It's in the garbage.

343
00:20:41,490 --> 00:20:42,741
It has willow-bark extract.

344
00:20:42,867 --> 00:20:44,826
Willow-bark extract
is basically aspirin.

345
00:20:44,952 --> 00:20:46,286
Yes, for the fever.

346
00:20:46,412 --> 00:20:48,413
He's already on meds, our meds.

347
00:20:48,539 --> 00:20:51,166
We can't risk any
adverse interactions.

348
00:20:51,292 --> 00:20:53,585
We need all this stuff to go.
We need to control this environment.

349
00:20:53,711 --> 00:20:56,171
So do we. People get sick
for a reason,

350
00:20:56,297 --> 00:20:57,923
'cause something in their life
is out of balance.

351
00:20:58,049 --> 00:21:01,092
Dad, he's a doctor.
He doesn't want to hear your talk.

352
00:21:01,218 --> 00:21:04,262
Balance is just starting to be restored
now that that girl is gone.

353
00:21:04,388 --> 00:21:06,640
That girl took pretty good care
of your son while you were away.

354
00:21:06,766 --> 00:21:08,725
Yes, we can see that.

355
00:21:08,851 --> 00:21:11,603
Look, all this stuff may make him feel
more comfortable, but it's not gonna...

356
00:21:11,729 --> 00:21:12,812
How long is this treatment
gonna take?

357
00:21:12,939 --> 00:21:14,459
We should start to see
some improvement

358
00:21:14,523 --> 00:21:15,440
in his liver function soon.

359
00:21:15,566 --> 00:21:18,109
Soon. Very scientific.

360
00:21:22,907 --> 00:21:24,074
I'm sorry.

361
00:21:30,539 --> 00:21:33,166
I'll be back in a little bit
to check on you.

362
00:21:38,923 --> 00:21:41,633
Ah, yes, if it isn't
Dr. Ironside.

363
00:21:41,759 --> 00:21:44,970
Ah, if it isn't Dr. "I Had No Friends
When I Was Growing Up",

364
00:21:45,096 --> 00:21:46,763
"So All I Did Was Watch TV
by Myself,."

365
00:21:46,889 --> 00:21:49,329
"Which Is Why I Can Now Make
Constant Pop-Culture References."

366
00:21:49,392 --> 00:21:51,184
"Which No One Understands
but Me."

367
00:21:51,310 --> 00:21:53,561
That's my name.
Don't wear it out.

368
00:21:56,023 --> 00:21:59,901
Safe from Cuddy, but I guess not
from her trusted rat-complice.

369
00:22:00,027 --> 00:22:03,405
Reasonable people don't debate
the relative merits of their handicaps.

370
00:22:03,531 --> 00:22:06,324
Reasonable people
make rules based on evidence,

371
00:22:06,450 --> 00:22:08,660
like difficulty
covering a distance,

372
00:22:08,786 --> 00:22:12,330
say, 50 yards, not on
some preordained patheticness scale.

373
00:22:12,456 --> 00:22:15,333
Last I checked, pigheadedness
was not the eighth heavenly virtue.

374
00:22:15,459 --> 00:22:17,877
It's only pigheaded if you're wrong.
If you're right,

375
00:22:18,004 --> 00:22:19,724
they call it,
"Sticking to your principles."

376
00:22:19,839 --> 00:22:21,381
Give it up.
You're demeaning yourself.

377
00:22:21,507 --> 00:22:23,133
That's what they told
Rosa Parks.

378
00:22:23,259 --> 00:22:25,885
Don't stand up in there.
I'm watching your feet.

379
00:22:26,762 --> 00:22:28,304
Get out of our home.

380
00:22:28,431 --> 00:22:30,432
This is not a home.
It's certainly not...

381
00:22:30,558 --> 00:22:31,933
It's our home as long as
our son is here.

382
00:22:32,059 --> 00:22:35,270
Mom, Dad, will you please
just calm down.

383
00:22:35,396 --> 00:22:38,565
You're not family.
You have no right to be here.

384
00:22:38,691 --> 00:22:41,067
What are you gonna do? Throw me out?
You can't even touch the gadje.

385
00:22:41,193 --> 00:22:43,236
- I'll touch you.
- What is going on?

386
00:22:43,362 --> 00:22:46,114
I'm the one who brought him here.
I should be able to see how he's doing.

387
00:22:46,240 --> 00:22:48,401
He wouldn't even need to be here
if it weren't for you.

388
00:22:48,492 --> 00:22:51,244
Right. I'm so unclean,
I caused his liver to shut down.

389
00:22:51,370 --> 00:22:53,329
Enough. No one is leaving.

390
00:22:53,456 --> 00:22:55,331
He's our son,
and we want her out of here.

391
00:22:58,210 --> 00:23:00,503
- It hurts.
- It's your stomach again?

392
00:23:00,629 --> 00:23:02,589
- No.
- What?

393
00:23:10,890 --> 00:23:13,349
His liver's actually improving.

394
00:23:13,476 --> 00:23:15,685
We plug one hole
and end up poking another.

395
00:23:15,811 --> 00:23:18,411
Are we talking about the patient
or how to get a raise from Cuddy?

396
00:23:18,481 --> 00:23:21,232
The Wegener's treatment gave him
a massive hemorrhage in his bladder.

397
00:23:21,358 --> 00:23:24,027
Which means it's Wegener's.

398
00:23:24,153 --> 00:23:26,473
- What did I just say?
- We were treating him for Wegener's

399
00:23:26,530 --> 00:23:28,156
- when everything went wrong.
- Not everything.

400
00:23:28,282 --> 00:23:30,867
Yeah, it was a very
lovely day outside.

401
00:23:30,993 --> 00:23:33,536
On the other hand,
the treatment made him worse.

402
00:23:33,662 --> 00:23:35,747
Treatment made his
bladder worse, not his liver.

403
00:23:35,873 --> 00:23:37,123
Clot in the liver's
breaking up.

404
00:23:37,249 --> 00:23:41,628
And MRI, sputum and ACE
ruled out TB, sarcoidosis and lymphoma,

405
00:23:41,754 --> 00:23:42,962
which leaves us with...

406
00:23:43,089 --> 00:23:44,255
Still could be
a cancer with multiple...

407
00:23:44,381 --> 00:23:47,383
A cancer we can't see
on MRI, CT or blood tests?

408
00:23:48,385 --> 00:23:49,928
It's Wegener's.

409
00:23:50,054 --> 00:23:52,472
It's not the wrong diagnosis.
It's the wrong treatment.

410
00:23:52,598 --> 00:23:55,141
We could increase immunosuppression.
Add methotrexate.

411
00:23:55,267 --> 00:23:58,645
We can't give methotrexate to a kid
who's already had lung problems.

412
00:23:58,771 --> 00:24:02,482
Methotrexate is carpet bombing.
Hits everything.

413
00:24:02,858 --> 00:24:04,526
We need a smart bomb.

414
00:24:04,652 --> 00:24:09,405
We don't suppress the immune system.
We change it.

415
00:24:09,824 --> 00:24:15,620
Immune modulation. FT28. His antibodies
are attacking his blood vessels.

416
00:24:15,746 --> 00:24:18,873
The irritation causes it to bleed
and clot. We change his immune system

417
00:24:18,999 --> 00:24:21,251
so the antibodies don't interact
with his blood vessels

418
00:24:21,377 --> 00:24:22,877
but work fine everywhere else.

419
00:24:23,003 --> 00:24:25,797
FT28 is still experimental.
It's not FDA approved.

420
00:24:25,923 --> 00:24:28,466
It's worked for Crohn's disease
and rheumatoid arthritis.

421
00:24:28,592 --> 00:24:31,136
He doesn't have Crohn's
or arthritis.

422
00:24:31,262 --> 00:24:35,306
Let's say that he does
and start the treatment.

423
00:24:41,856 --> 00:24:43,481
Absolutely not.

424
00:24:43,607 --> 00:24:46,067
My people have been experimented on
before. Never again.

425
00:24:46,193 --> 00:24:48,695
Mister Lipa,
with all due respect,

426
00:24:48,821 --> 00:24:52,157
comparing this hospital
with Auschwitz, it's ridiculous.

427
00:24:52,283 --> 00:24:54,450
FT28 has been proven
safe in hundreds...

428
00:24:54,577 --> 00:24:56,035
People always say
you can trust them.

429
00:24:56,162 --> 00:24:57,287
Why would they
say anything else?

430
00:24:57,413 --> 00:24:58,872
Why do they think
we would listen?

431
00:24:58,998 --> 00:25:01,207
You think I don't understand
what it's like to come from a people

432
00:25:01,333 --> 00:25:03,501
who've been enslaved,
mistreated and experimented on?

433
00:25:03,627 --> 00:25:06,504
Tuskegee went on for 28 years
after World War II.

434
00:25:06,630 --> 00:25:08,882
And the laws that made it illegal
for the Romany to even set foot

435
00:25:09,008 --> 00:25:13,303
in this state were still on the books
until 1998. It's not ancient history.

436
00:25:13,429 --> 00:25:18,141
Conventional therapy hasn't worked.
Your son may be dying.

437
00:25:19,894 --> 00:25:24,022
He needs a targeted approach,
and you need to trust us.

438
00:25:27,818 --> 00:25:32,280
I'm sorry. A lifetime of experiences
tells me I can't trust you,

439
00:25:32,406 --> 00:25:35,241
and the past three days
have done nothing to change that.

440
00:25:36,035 --> 00:25:38,953
We want our son treated,
not experimented on.

441
00:25:39,079 --> 00:25:41,119
If you don't know how to
do that, then just tell us,

442
00:25:41,207 --> 00:25:43,750
so we can take him
someplace where they do.

443
00:25:44,043 --> 00:25:46,711
They're absolutely right.
Stay away

444
00:25:46,837 --> 00:25:49,756
from that unproven, experimental stuff.
Much better to stick

445
00:25:49,882 --> 00:25:52,091
with the "moving the furniture
until he gets better" approach.

446
00:25:52,218 --> 00:25:54,427
Yes, you're right. We're gonna
have to come up with something else.

447
00:25:54,553 --> 00:25:58,640
Do you mean another last-ditch,
desperation move? You got anything?

448
00:25:58,766 --> 00:26:01,809
Go back and don't take no for an answer.
What kind of salesman are you?

449
00:26:01,936 --> 00:26:03,978
The kind who avoids the house
with the crazy couple

450
00:26:04,104 --> 00:26:05,355
who put tin foil
over their windows.

451
00:26:05,481 --> 00:26:06,602
They got money for tin foil,

452
00:26:06,607 --> 00:26:07,982
they got money for
whatever you're selling.

453
00:26:08,108 --> 00:26:09,859
What's that mean?

454
00:26:09,985 --> 00:26:13,696
It means that if they don't trust you,
you should earn that lack of trust.

455
00:26:13,822 --> 00:26:15,782
What does paying
for tinfoil mean?

456
00:26:15,908 --> 00:26:18,826
Why should I have
to answer all the questions?

457
00:26:22,998 --> 00:26:24,165
Oops.

458
00:26:24,291 --> 00:26:26,834
Sorry. Still getting used to
the power steering.

459
00:26:27,962 --> 00:26:29,202
I assume you've heard the news?

460
00:26:29,255 --> 00:26:30,255
I'm not worried.

461
00:26:30,381 --> 00:26:33,591
From what I hear, what you lack
in shame, you also lack in willpower.

462
00:26:33,717 --> 00:26:36,719
My will may be weak,
but my backbone is strong

463
00:26:36,845 --> 00:26:39,722
and pain-free
now that I've stopped using the cane.

464
00:26:39,848 --> 00:26:41,975
Of course, it's harder
to look down Cuddy's shirt,

465
00:26:42,101 --> 00:26:45,353
but then the vantage point
on her ass has much improved.

466
00:26:45,479 --> 00:26:47,772
Then that's just me,
always looking on the bright side.

467
00:26:47,898 --> 00:26:50,775
I'm the guy who said
that her C-cups are half full.

468
00:26:51,527 --> 00:26:53,736
They are nice, aren't they?

469
00:26:55,531 --> 00:27:00,493
Oh, no, no, no, you're not
gonna win me over that easily.

470
00:27:01,704 --> 00:27:04,163
You may have a wheel.
It doesn't mean you get the grease.

471
00:27:04,290 --> 00:27:06,082
You gotta squeak.

472
00:27:20,973 --> 00:27:22,265
What's that?

473
00:27:22,391 --> 00:27:23,683
It's cyclophosphamide.

